Exercise 1: Scatterplot

Using the gapminder07 data, create a scatterplot of the natural log of gdpPercap as a function of the natural log of pop. Give it a title and axis labels.

Remember, you will need three functions: ggplot(), geom_point(), and labs().

library(ggplot2)

Exercise 2: Hydro power generated over time

Task: Plot a column chart hydroelectric power generated over time.

Hint: There are two types of hydroelectric sources in the data: large_hydro and small_hydro.

library(dplyr)
long_gen %>% 
    filter(source %in% c('large_hydro', 'small_hydro')) %>% 
    group_by(datetime) %>% 
    summarise(output_sum = sum(output)) %>% 
    ggplot() + geom_col(aes(x = datetime, y = output_sum)) + 
    labs(title = 'Hydroelectric power generated', x = 'Hour', y = 'Hydroelectric power (MW)')

Exercise 3: Total output per source

Task: Create a column chart that shows the total output per source.

  • Change the color of the columns to "darkred".
  • Add a horizontal line indicating the mean output across all sources. Use the cheatsheet to identify the geom function that you need.
  • Add a meaningful title and axis labels using labs().
long_gen %>% 
    group_by(source) %>% 
    summarise(output = sum(output)) %>% 
    ggplot() + geom_col(aes(x = source, y = output), fill = 'darkred') +
    geom_hline(aes(yintercept = mean(output))) +
    geom_hline(aes(yintercept = median(output)), linetype = 'dashed') +
    labs(title = 'Total energy generated by each resource', x = 'Resource', y ='Output (MW)') +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45))

Exercise 4: Colors and fill

Task: Create a line plot that compares generation of wind, solar, and geothermal energy over time.

Bonus: Set the line size to 1.5.

long_gen %>% 
    filter(source %in% c('wind', 'solar', 'geothermal')) %>% 
    ggplot() + 
    geom_line(aes(x = datetime, y = output, group = source, col = source), size = 1.5) +
    labs(title = 'Wind vs. Solar vs. Geothermal generation', y = 'Output (MW)', x = 'Hour',
         subtitle = "Hourly data from September 3-9, 2018")

Exercise 5: Average hourly output by source

Task: Visualize the average output for each hour of the day, grouped by source.

Hint: You need to identify the output per source per hour (e.g.01:00, 02:00, etc) averaged over all days.

  • You will need to prepare your data using both dplyr and lubridate functions.
  • You can choose which geom(s) to use, and how to demarcate groups.
  • Bonus: use a scale layer to set a color palette (try "Set3") and change the legend name.
  • Remember to add labs()!
library(lubridate)
## 
## Attaching package: 'lubridate'
## The following object is masked from 'package:here':
## 
##     here
## The following object is masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     date
long_gen %>% 
    mutate(hour = hour(datetime)) %>% 
    group_by(hour, source) %>% 
    summarise(mean_output = mean(output, na.rm = T)) %>% 
    ggplot() +
    geom_area(aes(x = hour, y = mean_output, fill = factor(source))) +
    scale_fill_brewer(palette = 'Set3', name = 'Energy source') + 
    labs(title = 'Average hourly output by energy source', x = 'Hour of the day', 
         y ='Output (MW)')

Exercise 6: Facets

Task: Compare generation patterns for each source in facets. Color the lines using the group variable in regroup.

Remember: - You will need to prepare your data. Think about the variables that you need: source/type, output, and group. - When you pipe modified data into ggplot, remember that you are grouping in two ways: source/type through facets, and group through color.

long_gen_group <- merge(long_gen, regroup, by.x = 'source', by.y = 'type')
long_gen_group %>% 
    ggplot() +
    geom_line(aes(x = datetime, y = output, col = factor(group))) +
    facet_wrap(~ source, scales = 'free') + 
    # specify the choice of scales, in case some sources just have a horizontal line of output
    scale_color_brewer(palette = 'Set3', name = 'Energy group') + 
    labs(title = 'Average hourly output by energy source', x = 'Hour', y ='Output (MW)') +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45), legend.position = "bottom") + theme_bw()
